Day 20: Configure Nginx + PHP-FPM Using Unix Socket
📌 Project Overview

Modern PHP applications require a web server to handle incoming HTTP requests and an application runtime to execute PHP code. Rather than executing PHP directly, 
Nginx delegates PHP processing to PHP-FPM (FastCGI Process Manager) using a Unix socket, which offers lower latency and improved security compared to TCP communication.

In this project, I configured Nginx and PHP-FPM 8.3 on Nautilus App Server 2 to serve a PHP application through a Unix socket. The deployment included installing 
 the required packages, configuring Nginx to listen on a custom port, enabling FastCGI communication, and validating the application from the jump host.

🎯 Project Objective

The goal of this lab was to:

Install and configure Nginx on App Server 2.
Configure Nginx to listen on port 8091.
Set the document root to /var/www/html.
Install PHP-FPM 8.3.
Configure PHP-FPM to communicate through the Unix socket:
/var/run/php-fpm/default.sock
Integrate Nginx with PHP-FPM using FastCGI.
Verify the PHP application is accessible from the jump host.

